<paragraph id="E97036DD3F6DFFFAFF76FE57FF07FDD2" blockId="88.[151,1437,464,1463]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Note: This species was described recently and we lack information on its aspect and coloration in life; the present account is thus provisional and may not allow for a fully reliable visual identification and differentiation from 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F6DFFFAFA67FE73FF00FDD3" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1827" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Zebrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zebrus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFA67FE73FA76FDEF" box="[1414,1430,501,526]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Z</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFF76FD9EFF00FDD3" box="[151,224,536,562]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">zebrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F6DFFFAFF26FDBAFB1BFA56" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F6DFFFAFF26FDBAFD00FDB7" blockId="88.[151,1437,464,1463]" box="[199,736,572,599]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Size. Maximum known size 
<quantity id="2E379B383F6DFFFAFDE6FDBAFDB3FDB6" box="[519,595,572,599]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="cm" value="4.1">4.1 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F6DFFFAFF26FDE6FC4DFC97" blockId="88.[151,1437,464,1463]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Morphology. D VI + I,10–11; A I,8–9; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFD95FDE6FD45FD9B" bold="true" box="[628,677,608,634]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">P 17</emphasis>
. Small goby with a body more slender than in 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F6DFFFAFB49FDE6FAA5FD9B" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1827" box="[1192,1349,608,634]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Zebrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zebrus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFB49FDE6FAA5FD9B" box="[1192,1349,608,634]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Zebrus zebrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a large and somewhat flattened head, and a deep caudal peduncle of almost same depth as body. Eyes relatively small, snout slightly longer than eye diameter. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFDF0FD2EFC0EFD23" bold="true" box="[529,1006,680,706]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Head wide, with large prominent cheeks</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F6DFFFAFC1CFD2EFBBEFD23" box="[1021,1118,680,706]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1631,1655]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-18@31.[151,1437,181,1607]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 29. Zebrus pallaoroi. A) Freshly dead coloration, transverse coloration pattern with pale vertical bars. B) Live coloration in its natural habitat, pattern reduced to pale dorsal saddles while the rest of body lateral side is more or less uniformly colored or mottled dark. C) anterior nostril with tentacle.A) and B) photos of the same individual. Photos by J. Renoult, Palavasles-Flots, Southern France." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601659/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 29c</figureCitation>
): head width at opercle level about 80–90 % of head length (compared to 50–75 % in 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F6DFFFAFCC7FD4BFC6EFD07" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1827" box="[806,910,716,743]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Zebrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zebrus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFCC7FD4BFCD6FD07" box="[806,822,717,742]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Z</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFCA4FD4AFC6EFD07" box="[837,910,716,742]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">zebrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFC46FD4AFABDFD07" bold="true" box="[935,1373,716,742]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Anterior nostril a tube with tentacle</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F6DFFFAFA8EFD4AFF23FCEB" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1631,1655]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-18@31.[151,1437,181,1607]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 29. Zebrus pallaoroi. A) Freshly dead coloration, transverse coloration pattern with pale vertical bars. B) Live coloration in its natural habitat, pattern reduced to pale dorsal saddles while the rest of body lateral side is more or less uniformly colored or mottled dark. C) anterior nostril with tentacle.A) and B) photos of the same individual. Photos by J. Renoult, Palavasles-Flots, Southern France." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601659/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 29c</figureCitation>
); posterior nostril tube only slightly shorter (more than 80 % of the anterior). Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin with more or less rounded margin. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFD26FC92FA7CFCCF" bold="true" box="[711,1436,788,814]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">The uppermost pectoral-fin rays partly free from membrane</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F6DFFFAFF7EFCBEFE9FFCB3" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R. &amp; Cekovska, K. &amp; Soukupova, T. &amp; Vukic, J." box="[159,383,824,851]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="285 - 317" refId="ref59357" refString="Kovacic, M., Sanda, R., Cekovska, K., T. Soukupova, T. &amp; Vukic, J. (2021) Zebrus pallaoroi sp. nov.: a new species of goby (Actinopterygii: Gobiidae) from the Mediterranean Sea with a dna-based phylogenetic analysis of the Gobius - lineage. Contributions to Zoology Advance articles, 90 (3), 285 - 317 https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 18759866 - bja 10018" type="journal article" year="2021">
Kovačić 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFEE4FCBFFED6FCB3" box="[261,310,824,850]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">et al</emphasis>
. 2021
</bibRefCitation>
; present work). Caudal fin rounded. Body scaled, nape and predorsal area naked. Scales more or less visible on body from reticulate pigmentation along scale edges.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F6DFFFAFF26FC06FB69FB77" blockId="88.[151,1437,464,1463]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Coloration. In dead or preserved specimens, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFD20FC06FB9DFC7B" bold="true" box="[705,1149,896,922]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">body with 10−11 pale bars along side</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F6DFFFAFB6CFC06FABAFC7A" box="[1165,1370,896,923]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1631,1655]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-18@31.[151,1437,181,1607]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 29. Zebrus pallaoroi. A) Freshly dead coloration, transverse coloration pattern with pale vertical bars. B) Live coloration in its natural habitat, pattern reduced to pale dorsal saddles while the rest of body lateral side is more or less uniformly colored or mottled dark. C) anterior nostril with tentacle.A) and B) photos of the same individual. Photos by J. Renoult, Palavasles-Flots, Southern France." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601659/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Figs. 29a and 29b</figureCitation>
), first in front of the first dorsal fin, last at the end of the second dorsal fin. Very little is known for sure about this species’ 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFF76FC4FFF05FC03" box="[151,229,969,994]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">in vivo</emphasis>
coloration. Overall live coloration dark to pale brownish or greenish with thin, alternating, pale and dark bars (*). Usually, there are 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFE27FC6AFC30FBE7" bold="true" box="[454,976,1004,1030]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">at least 4 pale bars under the first dorsal fin</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F6DFFFAFC3EFC6AFB4AFBE6" box="[991,1194,1004,1031]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1631,1655]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-18@31.[151,1437,181,1607]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 29. Zebrus pallaoroi. A) Freshly dead coloration, transverse coloration pattern with pale vertical bars. B) Live coloration in its natural habitat, pattern reduced to pale dorsal saddles while the rest of body lateral side is more or less uniformly colored or mottled dark. C) anterior nostril with tentacle.A) and B) photos of the same individual. Photos by J. Renoult, Palavasles-Flots, Southern France." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601659/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Figs. 29a and 29b</figureCitation>
), but this pattern may disappear, the sides of body becoming uniformly colored or mottled dark. When present, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFB7EFB96FF31FBAF" bold="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">the crescent band on head</emphasis>
(broad pale transverse band across anterior nape extending on the sides reaching pectoral-fin bases) 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFAD8FBB2FE45FB93" bold="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">does not extend forward to eyes</emphasis>
. First dorsal fin usually with a whitish longitudinal band, topped with a contrasting orangeyellow to pinkish distal half. Second dorsal fin with dark spots seldom coalescing in lines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F6DFFFAFF26FB26FAB9FB3E" blockId="88.[151,1437,464,1463]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
(*) The pattern of lateral bars visible on dead or stressed animals do not exactly match the number and location of lateral markings usually displayed underwater (these 2 pattern 
<typeStatus id="3674887F3F6DFFFAFC95FB43FC4FFB3E" box="[884,943,1221,1247]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">types</typeStatus>
may superimpose to various extents).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F6DFFFAFF26FB6EFB75FAE2" blockId="88.[151,1437,464,1463]" box="[199,1173,1256,1283]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F6DFFFAFE9EFB6EFDFDFAE3" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1827" box="[383,541,1256,1282]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Zebrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zebrus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFE9EFB6EFDFDFAE3" box="[383,541,1256,1282]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Zebrus zebrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F6DFFFAFDCAFB6EFC95FAE3" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Kolombatovic" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[555,885,1256,1282]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Millerigobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrocephalus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFDCAFB6EFC95FAE3" box="[555,885,1256,1282]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Millerigobius macrocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F6DFFFAFC62FB6EFB6EFAE3" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Kolombatovic" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[899,1166,1256,1282]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Chromogobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zebratus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFC62FB6EFB6EFAE3" box="[899,1166,1256,1282]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Chromogobius zebratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F6DFFFAFF26FA8AFC5DFAAA" blockId="88.[151,1437,464,1463]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Habitat. Shallow infralittoral species, known from 
<quantity id="2E379B383F6DFFFAFD1FFA8AFCA5FAC6" box="[766,837,1292,1319]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="m" value="0.5" valueMax="1.0" valueMin="0.0">0–1 m</quantity>
depth between gravel and small boulders (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F6DFFFAFAC3FA8AFF16FAAB" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R. &amp; Cekovska, K. &amp; Soukupova, T. &amp; Vukic, J." pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="285 - 317" refId="ref59357" refString="Kovacic, M., Sanda, R., Cekovska, K., T. Soukupova, T. &amp; Vukic, J. (2021) Zebrus pallaoroi sp. nov.: a new species of goby (Actinopterygii: Gobiidae) from the Mediterranean Sea with a dna-based phylogenetic analysis of the Gobius - lineage. Contributions to Zoology Advance articles, 90 (3), 285 - 317 https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 18759866 - bja 10018" type="journal article" year="2021">
Kovačić 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFA69FA8BFF4DFAAB" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">et al</emphasis>
. 2021
</bibRefCitation>
, 2022). Also found at 
<quantity id="2E379B383F6DFFFAFE0FFAB6FDF9FAAA" box="[494,537,1328,1355]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="m" value="3.0">3 m</quantity>
depth (J. Renoult, unpublished data).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F6DFFFAFF26FAD2FB1BFA56" blockId="88.[151,1437,464,1463]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Geographic distribution. Mediterranean. Recorded in the southern, central and northern part along the eastern Adriatic Sea, the northern part of the Ionian Sea, and the northern and western parts of the Aegean Sea (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F6DFFFAFAC3FAFEFF16FA57" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Sanda, R. &amp; Cekovska, K. &amp; Soukupova, T. &amp; Vukic, J." pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="285 - 317" refId="ref59357" refString="Kovacic, M., Sanda, R., Cekovska, K., T. Soukupova, T. &amp; Vukic, J. (2021) Zebrus pallaoroi sp. nov.: a new species of goby (Actinopterygii: Gobiidae) from the Mediterranean Sea with a dna-based phylogenetic analysis of the Gobius - lineage. Contributions to Zoology Advance articles, 90 (3), 285 - 317 https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 18759866 - bja 10018" type="journal article" year="2021">
Kovačić 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F6DFFFAFA69FAFFFF4DFA57" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">et al</emphasis>
. 2021
</bibRefCitation>
, 2022). Also known from Palavas-les-Flots, southern 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F6DFFFAFCB1FA1BFC7CFA56" box="[848,924,1437,1463]" name="France" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">France</collectingCountry>
(J. Renoult, unpublished data).
</paragraph>
